The '''Gold Blend couple''' was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[television advertising]] campaign for [[Nescafé]] Gold Blend [[instant coffee]]. The original campaign ran for twelve 45-second instalments between [[1987 in television|1987]] and [[1993 in television|1993]]. It starred [[Anthony Head]] and [[Sharon Maughan]] as Tony and Sharon, a couple who begin a slow-burning romance over a cup of the advertised coffee. The ads were in a [[serial (radio and television)|serial]] format, with each ad ending on a [[cliffhanger]]. The commercials were extremely popular, and as time went on, the appearance of a new instalment would merit considerable media attention. The ads were developed by [[McCann Erickson]]. They are one of the most famous examples of serialized advertising.

Beginning in 1990, new versions of the ads were produced for the [[United States|American]] market, where Gold Blend was called "Taster's Choice," and the ads were referred to as the "Taster's Choice saga". Head and Maughan reprised their roles, but used American accents in the reshot ads. After the first two nearly identical ads, the American ads diverged into their own storyline.

The campaign was a remarkable success, producing various tie-in products, including a novelization entitled ''Love Over Gold'' by [[Susan Moody]], a video compilation of the ads, and two music CDs. The ads had a notable effect on sales, increasing them over 50% in the UK alone. They have been heralded as a premier example of [[positioning (marketing)|positioning]], creating an atmosphere of sophistication while remaining relatable. They were frequently compared to a [[soap opera]], even sometimes favorably compared to their contemporaries, such as ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', or ''[[thirtysomething (TV series)|thirtysomething]]''. Famously, Head and Maughan appeared on the cover of ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' after their campaign concluded and the two characters confessed their love for each other.

In later years, there were two additional series of ads starring new couples. The second series starred [[Louise Hunt]] and [[Mark Aiken]] and focused on a younger, more career-oriented woman, running for six instalments until 1997. In 1998, a new version with [[Simone Bendix]] and [[Neil Roberts (actor)|Neil Roberts]] began, but the campaign was discontinued after only one ad.

In 2005, the campaign ranked at number 20 on "[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s Best Ever Ads".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thinkbox.tv/server/show/nav.943 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305130459/http://thinkbox.tv/server/show/nav.943 |archivedate=2009-03-05 |df= }}</ref> It had ranked at number 31 in a [[100 Greatest (UK TV series)|similar list]] compiled in 2000 aired on [[Channel 4]].<ref>http://www.uktvadverts.com/facts/?list=ch4</ref>

